Understanding when React runs side effects and why the dependency array matters
When I first started learning React, useState felt fairly intuitive. I could update a value, React would re-render the component, and I could immediately see the result on the screen. The relationship between state and UI was easy to understand.
useEffect was a different story.
For a while, it felt like a catch-all solution for problems I didn’t fully understand. Need to fetch data? Use useEffect. Need something to run once when the page loads? Use useEffect. Seeing strange re-render behavior? There is probably a useEffectinvolved somewhere. While those observations are not entirely wrong, they do not explain what the hook is actually designed to do.
The explanation that finally made it click for me came from the React documentation:
useEffect lets a component synchronize with something outside of React.
That outside system might be an API, a browser feature, a timer, local storage, or some other service React does not control. Once I started thinking about useEffect as a synchronization tool instead of a place to put "extra code," the hook became much easier to understand.

React Renders First, Effects Run After
At its core, React’s primary responsibility is rendering user interfaces. Components receive props and state, then return JSX that describes what should appear on the screen.
Consider the following component:
function PlayerCard({ player }) {
return (
<div>
<h2>{player.name}</h2>
<p>Goals: {player.goals}</p>
</div>
);
}This component does not need useEffect. It simply receives data and displays it. React handles everything required during the render process.
However, sometimes we need to interact with something that exists outside of React. Imagine we want the browser tab title to update whenever a player changes. The browser’s document.title is not managed by React, so we need a way to synchronize it with our component.
import { useEffect } from "react";function PlayerCard({ player }) {
useEffect(() => {
document.title = `${player.name}'s Player Card`;
}, [player.name]);
return (
<div>
<h2>{player.name}</h2>
<p>Goals: {player.goals}</p>
</div>
);
}
In this example, React first renders the component. Once the render is complete, React runs the effect. This distinction is important because effects are not part of rendering itself. They happen after rendering and allow a component to stay synchronized with external systems.

The Dependency Array Controls When the Effect Runs
One of the most important parts of useEffect is the dependency array.
useEffect(() => {
document.title = `${player.name}'s Player Card`;
}, [player.name]);The dependency array tells React when an effect should run again. In this case, the effect runs after the initial render and then any time player.name changes.
A useful question to ask yourself is:
What values does this effect depend on?
If a player’s goals change, React does not need to update the browser title because the title only depends on the player’s name. Understanding dependencies helps prevent unnecessary effect executions and makes components easier to reason about.

Three Common Dependency Array Patterns
When learning useEffect, you will frequently encounter three common dependency array patterns.
1. No Dependency Array
useEffect(() => {
console.log("This runs after every render");
});Without a dependency array, React executes the effect after every render. While there are valid use cases for this behavior, it can also introduce bugs if the effect updates state and causes another render cycle.
2. Empty Dependency Array
useEffect(() => {
console.log("This runs once after the component first renders");
}, []);An empty dependency array tells React to run the effect only once after the initial render.
A common example is loading data when a page first appears:
import { useEffect, useState } from "react";function PlayersPage() {
const [players, setPlayers] = useState([]);
useEffect(() => {
fetch("http://localhost:3000/players")
.then((response) => response.json())
.then((data) => setPlayers(data));
}, []);
return (
<div>
{players.map((player) => (
<h2 key={player.id}>{player.name}</h2>
))}
</div>
);
}
This allows data to be fetched once without triggering additional requests on every render.
3. Dependencies Inside the Array
useEffect(() => {
console.log(`Selected player changed to ${selectedPlayer}`);
}, [selectedPlayer]);This pattern is the one developers use most often. The effect runs after the first render and again whenever selectedPlayerchanges. React only reruns the effect when one of its dependencies changes, making it both predictable and efficient.

Cleanup: Turning Off What You Turned On
Not all effects are one-time operations. Some create ongoing processes such as timers, subscriptions, or event listeners.
When that happens, React gives us a way to clean up those resources.
useEffect(() => {
const intervalId = setInterval(() => {
console.log("Still scouting...");
}, 1000); return () => {
clearInterval(intervalId);
};
}, []);
The function returned from useEffect is known as a cleanup function. React executes it before rerunning the effect or when the component is removed from the page.
A simple rule I use is:
If the effect turns something on, the cleanup should turn it off.
Keeping that rule in mind helps prevent memory leaks and unexpected behavior.

When You Probably Don’t Need useEffect
One lesson that surprised me while learning React is that many beginners use useEffect more often than necessary.
If a value can be calculated directly during rendering, an effect is usually unnecessary.
For example:
function PlayerStats({ goals, assists }) {
const points = goals + assists; return <p>Total Points: {points}</p>;
}
This works perfectly because points can be derived directly from the existing data.
Compare that to:
function PlayerStats({ goals, assists }) {
const [points, setPoints] = useState(0); useEffect(() => {
setPoints(goals + assists);
}, [goals, assists]);
return <p>Total Points: {points}</p>;
}
While this version works, it introduces additional state and an additional effect that React does not actually need. Whenever possible, keeping logic inside the render process is usually the simpler solution.

The Mental Model That Finally Made It Click
The mental model that helped me understand useEffect is surprisingly simple:
Render shows the page.
useEffect reacts to the page being shown or changed.
Before writing an effect, I now ask myself four questions:

• Am I synchronizing with something outside React?

• Does this need to happen after rendering?

• What value should cause this effect to run again?

• Do I need a cleanup function?
If the answer to the first question is no, I probably do not need useEffect.

Final Takeaway
At first, useEffect felt like one of React's most confusing hooks because it serves a different purpose than rendering. Components render UI. Effects synchronize that UI with systems outside of React.
Once I started viewing useEffect through that lens, the hook became much easier to understand. The dependency array stopped feeling like magic and started feeling like a tool for controlling when synchronization should happen.
The goal is not to use useEffect everywhere.
The goal is to understand exactly why you are using it.
